Hurricane Rosa threatens Phoenix, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City with major flooding (drought areas could benefit)
It is not common for a tropical depression to affect Arizona, but that is precisely what is likely to happen early next week when what is left of Hurricane Rosa passes through the southwestern desert, with the consequent risk of flooding.
The national weather service has already issued flood warnings for Monday and Tuesday in western Arizona to southern and eastern Nevada, southeastern California and Utah, including the cities of Phoenix, Flagstaff, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City.
Rosa is expected to arrive directly in Phoenix on Tuesday and approach it on a rainy Monday night.
The Phoenix National Weather Service said in a tweet that only "ten tropical cyclones have maintained tropical storm or depression status within a 322 km radius of Phoenix since 1950.
Hurricane Katrina (1967) was 40 miles (64 km) from the Arizona border.
