According to weather.com, "a total of 75 to 150 mm of rain is expected from Baja California to northwestern Sonora, with the possibility of up to 250 mm."
After that, Rosa will head north across Mexico with tropical storm force, before arriving at the Arizona border early Tuesday morning with tropical depression force, to finally cross Arizona and reach southern Utah well into Tuesday night.
"The main risk we expect from Rosa or what's left of it is very heavy rainfall in Baja California, northwestern Sonora and the desert southwest of the U.S.," according to the National Hurricane Center.
