Macedonians hold referendum to decide whether to change country's name
Last Sunday, the Macedonian people held a referendum on the name change to “Republic of Northern Macedonia”, a measure that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece, which had blocked Macedonia’s applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbour constitutes a claim to its territory and has banned it from joining NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's mostly Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not participate in the referendum, and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether the required 50 percent turnout will be reached for the referendum to be valid.
The question indicated on the ballot paper of the referendum is: <0xC2><0xAB>Are you in favor of joining NATO and the EU, with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?<0xC2><0xBB>.
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to achieve membership of Macedonia, one of the countries that were created in the wake of the breakup of Yugoslavia, in bodies such as the EU and NATO.
“Today I came to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because it means that all of us will have a safer life,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have stated that they will abide by the result of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority in Parliament is required.
The State Electoral Commission reported that there had been no irregularities at 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% recorded in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered people voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” Gjose Tanevski, 62, said in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dushko voted in the referendum held in Macedonia on the name change of the country, which would open the way for it to join the European Union and NATO in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Skopje Parliament, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents installed by the people who would boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of NATO and the EU, but we want to adhere to it with our heads held high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says joining NATO will be accompanied by more than necessary investments in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I think the vast majority will vote for it, because more than 80 percent of citizens are in favor of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
Zaev said a “yes” would be the “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Political Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of voters would take part in the referendum, a figure below the minimum turnout needed.
According to the results of another poll, conducted by the Macedonian TV channel Telma TV, 57% of those polled are expected to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote “yes.”
For the referendum to be valid, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would be the first hard blow to the policy of the pro-Western government since it took over in May last year.
