John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence that has continued into 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which is reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a very popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot depend only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages lead the ranking tables with the highest ratings in independent schools.
68% of the students who studied foreign languages obtained a higher A grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A grade.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are held in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave for struggling to fill vacancies, 17% was attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more potential job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those from developed economies, will give children better chances of finding an important job.
In Scotland there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages they teach.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be more important to the UK going forward, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, they can always choose from a range of languages at independent schools, which have specialist teaching staff in this area.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future throws at them.
In today’s global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communicative skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
