North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm "in any way" if no signs of confidence are seen
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying its mistrust of the United States and that, under such circumstances, the country would not unilaterally remove its nuclear weapons in any way.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center, and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not observe any consistent response from the US,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally initiate disarmament in any way.”
While Ri echoed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization approach for which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual action, his statements seemed significant in that he did not reject unilateral denuclearization outright, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referenced Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump’s joint statement at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that denuclearization must occur first and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal coercively, in addition to opposing the ‘declaration of an end to war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a chimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that continued sanctions are intensifying our mistrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added, “If the party involved in the denuclearization issue were South Korea instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this stalemate.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from what he delivered last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President “Mr. Evil” Trump dubbed Kim “Rocket Man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said much remained to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
Last Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for that and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the Security Council’s enforcement of sanctions must continue vigorously and without exception until we confirm full and final denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously pushed for sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in a bid to cut off funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic missile and nuclear programmes.
Pompeo met Ri outside the U.N. General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
