Harvard Students Take a Course on Rest Habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the culture, increasingly widespread, of studying throughout the night, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that students at the world’s number one university are often clueless about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are told the basics about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, slippers and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Below, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler said.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students make sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Making sure to enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes the last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
