Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and counting... the day that the physicist of the future, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device we know as the "Geiger counter".
The Geiger counter, which has been a pillar of science ever since, also became a pop culture pile, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, a seemingly unsuccessful cowboy physicist:
Man: “What the hell is that?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can hear the effects of the atoms emanating from the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "Sure it's exploding now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
