The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
New research on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape for food.
The findings are expected to provide new insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats as well as northern eared and water bats in the Inverewe Botanic Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to keep track of bat activities during the station.
Volunteers and staff from the UK’s National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with wearable detectors.
The sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and habitat map will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a natural conservation adviser at the Scottish National Foundation, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the UK has declined considerably in the last century.
The construction and restoration of buildings threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do flypaper and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to locate insects and obstacles that get in the way of their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who carry out surveys, inspections of nests and sometimes rescues on a regular basis.
The organisation has even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve on the Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The administrator of the estate, David Thompson, states that it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threate, we have a great area for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It stresses the importance of checking whether there are bats before doing maintenance tasks on properties, since it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, attack them, disturb them and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer with the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
“We still have a lot to learn from bats, and in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
