Jack Ross: "My ultimate ambition is to coach Scotland"
Sunderland manager Jack Ross has said his "maximum ambition" is to be Scotland's coach at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot has accepted the challenge of reviving the northeastern club, which currently occupies third place in League One, three points behind the leader.
He arrived at the Stadium of Light this summer after returning St Mirren to the Scottish Premiership last season.
“I wanted to play for my country when I was a player.
I was called in once as a supporter and that's it," Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportssound programme.
“But I grew up watching a lot of Scotland playing in Hampden with my father when I was little and it’s always something that takes me back in time.
This opportunity will only come to me if I succeed in coaching clubs, though.”
Ross's predecessors as manager of Sunderland include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic manager says he does not feel pressure to be next on a list of names enshrined in such a large team, having previously turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“At the moment, my criterion for measuring my success will be whether I can bring this team back to the Premier League.
“With the structure and facilities of the club, it is clear that its place is in the Premier League,” he said.
“It’s not easy to get there, but I would only consider that I’ve been successful here if I can bring the club back.”
Ross has only three years of coaching experience, following a stint as a second coach at Dumbarton and 15 months in the Hearts coaching staff.
He helped Alloa avoid relegation to the third tier and transformed St Mirren from fighting for salvation to Championship champions the following season.
Ross says he feels more comfortable now than during his time at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
“It was probably a decisive moment,” he recalled about accepting the position at Alloa.
“I always thought that training was the best thing for me, more than playing.
It sounds weird because I did it right, I got away with it reasonably well, and I enjoyed pretty good highs.
But playing can be hard.
There are a lot of things you have to overcome every week.
I’m still dealing with things like stress and pressure at work, but I feel good as a coach.
I’ve always wanted to train and now I’m doing it, it’s the most comfortable time I’ve felt since I was an adult.”
