Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have died as a result of a strong earthquake and tsunami that shook the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, according to authorities. The death toll is expected to rise.
As communications are cut off, the relief units have been unable to obtain information from the Donggala regency, an area north of Palu closest to the epicenter of the 7.5-magnitude earthquake.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated since the disaster.
Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebs:
Palu is the capital of Celebes Central Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Celebes Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 people in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami hit.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along more than 300 km of coastline northwest of Celebes Island.
The regency, a lower administrative region than a province, had a population of approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the mainstays of the economy of the Central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the coast at the other end of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to Indonesia’s disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami struck west of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Ring of Fire, and earthquakes occur there with some frequency.
Listed below are the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004 – On 26 December, a major earthquake off the west coast of the Indonesian province of Ace, north of Sumatra, triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people off the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that devastated the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 shook an area aft of the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 shook one of the islands of Mentawai, off the coast of Sumatra, and caused a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh and caused destruction and panic, as the population recalled the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people were killed by the buildings that fell.
2018: A series of large earthquakes occurred on the tourist Indonesian island of Lombok that killed over 500 people, mainly in the north of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily trapped.
