Syria 'ready' to return refugees, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for help to rebuild the country, ravaged by a war of more than seven years.
Speaking before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country were improving.
“Today, the situation on the street is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists destroyed to restore normalcy.
All conditions are met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their maintenance.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country in need of humanitarian aid.
