Red tide update: concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Spots can be found 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to the situation last week.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations have been reported on the coast or offshore in Pinellas County over the past week, concentrations from low to high offshore in Hillsborough County, concentrations from low to high offshore in Manatee County, concentrations from low to medium offshore in Charlotte County, concentrations from low to high offshore in Leeland County and concentrations from low to high offshore in Leeland County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeastern Florida.
